{"id":"1710.03201","submitter":"David Maxwell","authors":"James Dilts, Michael Holst, Tamara Kozareva, David Maxwell","title":"Numerical Bifurcation Analysis of the Conformal Method","comments":"22 pages, 14 figures; expanded and revised","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The conformal formulation of the Einstein constraint equations has been\nstudied intensively since the modern version of the conformal method was first\npub- lished in the early 1970s. Proofs of existence and uniqueness of solutions\nwere limited to the constant mean curvature (CMC) case through the early 90s,\nwith analogous results for the near-CMC case beginning to appear thereafter. In\nthe last decade, there has been some limited progress towards understanding the\nproperties of the conformal method for far-from-CMC solutions as well. Although\nit was initially conceivable that that these far-from-CMC results would lead to\na solution theory for the non-CMC case that would mirror the good properties of\nthe CMC and near-CMC cases, examples of bifurcations and of nonexistence of\nsolutions have been since discovered. Nevertheless, the general properties of\nthe conformal method for far-from-CMC data remain unknown. In this article we\napply analytic and numerical continuation techniques to the study of the con-\nformal method, in an attempt to give some insight into what the solution\nbehavior is in the far-from-CMC case in various scenarios.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 Oct 2017 17:24:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 6 Aug 2018 17:36:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-07"}
